Boil your #kettle{}. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Slice the @closed cup mushrooms{150%g}. Remove the ends from the @courgette{1}, halve lengthways and chop into 1cm chunks. Pick the @rosemary{4%sprigs} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Pour the @water{300%ml} into a #measuring jug{} and stir in the @chicken stock powder{1/2}.

Pop the @British pork loin steaks{2} in a #mixing bowl{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Drizzle on some @olive oil{} and sprinkle on half the rosemary. Rub the rosemary oil into the pork with your fingers and keep to one side.

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat!

Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{10%g}(finely chopped, stalks and all). In a #small bowl{}, mix the parsley with the @balsamic vinegar{12%ml} and @olive oil{3%ml}. This is your parsley drizzle.

Heat a splash of oil in a large #saucepan{} over medium-high heat. Add the mushrooms and cook until almost browned, stirring occasionally, ~{5%minutes}. Add the shallot, @tomato puree{30%g} and remaining rosemary and cook for another ~{2-3%minutes}, stirring often. Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} and then pour in the stock. Bring to a simmer, lower the heat to medium, cover with a #lid{} or #foil{} and leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}.

Five mins into the rice cooking time, add the courgette to the pan, quickly replace the lid and continue cooking for another ~{5%minutes}. When the rice has cooked for 10 mins total, remove from the heat and set aside (still covered) for another ~{10%minutes}.

> TIP: The courgette and rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

While the rice cooks, heat a #frying pan{} over medium-high heat and when the pan is hot, carefully lay in the pork steaks. Brown for ~{2%minutes} on each side and then lower the heat to medium. Cook until the pork is no longer pink in the middle, another ~{8%minutes}, turn every couple of mins. When the pork is cooked, remove from the heat and wrap loosely in foil to rest and keep warm.

To serve, fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Share between your plates. Slice the pork steaks and lay on top. Add any resting juices from the pork to the parsley drizzle and spoon this over the pork. Enjoy!